Successfully developed and deployed an automated computer vision pipeline to detect and extract defects from the DeepPCB dataset. 

- The system begins by pairing each test image with its correct template through a recursive folder search that matches files using board IDs, ensuring accurate template selection even when images are stored across multiple defect categories.
- It then performs image alignment using ORB feature descriptors and a homography transformation, enabling the pipeline to correct for camera shifts, rotations, and minor perspective changes before comparison.
- After alignment, the method applies reference-based subtraction followed by Otsuâ€™s thresholding to generate a binary defect mask. Morphological operations are used to remove noise and sharpen defect boundaries for more reliable detection.
- Contour detection is applied to identify defect regions on the processed mask. Bounding boxes are drawn for visualization, and each defect is cropped into a clean Region of Interest (ROI), creating a refined dataset suitable for further analysis or machine learning workflows.
